<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-637-882  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 637 882.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  June 20 1990 n135 p23(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Nixdorf turns in $633 million losses.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Nixdorf Computer Corp. (finance).andO;Topic:     Financial ReportLossesComputer Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Nixdorf turns in $633 million losses Nixdorf, the financially troubledcomputer company which announced its intentions to merge with Siemens at thebeginning of the year, has recorded a substantial group loss.andM;The company declared a net loss of $633 million for 1989, compared with a netprofit in 1988 of $15.6 million.andP;  Analysts were not surprised.andP;  &quot;It is stillpaying for mass expansions it carried out in 1987 and 1988, for which marketgrowth didn't correspond,&quot; commented one City analyst.andM;From 1 October, subject to shareholders' approval, Nixdorf will merge withSiemens' information technology division to form Europe's largest computermanufacturer, under the banner Siemens-Nixdorf Information Systems.andM;Nixdorf denied that its poor results will have an adverse affect on itsrelations with Siemens.andP;  &quot;It is a publicly known fact that we took onpersonnel during 1987 for a growth that didn't happen and have had to do somebroad restructuring to compensate,&quot; commented a spokeswoman for the company.andM;Since the beginning of the year, Nixdorf has been restructuring itsoperations with plans to cut ailing units and reduce its workforce.andO;</TEXT></DOC>